    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-22T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-22T02:00:00-05:00" n="687"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d687">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/10803: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tsingtao</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sokobin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tsingtao</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-22T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 22, 1937—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 22—1:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Mayor of Tsingtao invited me this morning to discuss the situation in
                    Tsinanfu, the capital of Shantung. He referred to numerous current rumors that
                    an agreement had been reached between Han Fu Chu and Japan executives [<hi
                        rend="italic">military?</hi>], that a Peace Preservation Commission had been
                    established in Tsinanfu which if true would commit Shantung to a separate policy
                    and freedom of action in north. The Mayor went at length to explain that he had
                    denied negotiation of such an agreement with Japan and had “severely rebuked”
                    the leaders of the Peace Preservation Commission movement. It appears to the
                    Consulate that the Mayor’s elaborate explanation was intended to cover what was
                    probably already a <hi rend="italic">fait accompli</hi>, that is a Han-Japanese
                    understanding in regard to Shantung and a movement in Tsingtao [for?] separation
                    from Nanking in the politico-military sphere.</p>
                <p>Sent to Nanking, Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sokobin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
